I dug into what was causing the failure of our file and found some valuable info.

### Background
We are running a document processor in AWS Lambda by pulling the file data from S3 and parsing `xlsx` files with ExcelJS.
```typescript
const workbook = new Workbook();
const buffer = this.getBuffer(body); // body is S3 bucket object body, returns Buffer
await workbook.xlsx.load(buffer);
```
We had no issue loading some `xlsx` files but then would fail to load others.  Failure in our context meant either hitting our Lambda execution time or memory limits (even at a memory limit of 10,240MB!).

### Discovery
I found that our particular file was failing when we were parsing the `dataValidations` for one of the worksheets of the file we uploaded, particularly when a data validation was being applied to each address in range:

```javascript
// exceljs/lib/xlsx/xform/sheet/data-validations-xform.js line: 217
// ... on closing name = 'dataValidation'
  parseClose(name) {
    switch (name) {
      case 'dataValidations':
        return false;
      case 'dataValidation': {
        if (!this._dataValidation.formulae || !this._dataValidation.formulae.length) {
          delete this._dataValidation.formulae;
          delete this._dataValidation.operator;
        }
        // The four known cases: 1. E4:L9 N4:U9  2.E4 L9  3. N4:U9  4. E4
        const list = this._address.split(/\s+/g) || [];
        list.forEach(addr => {
          if (addr.includes(':')) {
            const range = new Range(addr);
            range.forEachAddress(address => {
              this.model[address] = this._dataValidation;
            });
          } else {
            this.model[addr] = this._dataValidation;
          }
        });
        return true;
      }
      // ...
  }
```
Addresses for us when we were failing were (`console.log('this._address', this._address);`):
