```
What stood out to me were a few ranges like `Q1436:R1048576` and `O1458:P1048576`, where each cell in the range is assigned the `dataValidation` via a Javascript object map.  With so many cells in these ranges, our function memory (and runtime) get blown through the roof.

Once I cleared out all of the data validation on the worksheet, we were able to parse the file without issue.

### Discussion

It seems to me that ranges like these are created in Excel when entire columns are set to have particular data validation, and then later on, row inserts, copy/pastes, or fills override the data validation for a subset of the cells in those columns, forcing Excel to break the once contiguous range of `A:A` for example into separate `A1:A10` and `A12:A[infinity]` ranges, except Excel uses 10^20 (1048576) instead of "infinity."  Because Excel instead saves the separate ranges that are so large, it causes ExcelJS to go nuclear with memory usage when loading the file in situations where it is creating a Javascript object map entry for each cell.

I don't have a solution to this problem.  My only thoughts are perhaps to recognize when a range is going to "infinity" in situations where you might try to allocate memory for all cells in the range and to have the option to prevent that from happening.  Ideally, ExcelJS might be able to figure out where the last row/column contains "real" information and be able to stop "infinite ranges" from going beyond that row or column or some offset from that row or column.  I'm open to discussion.

NOTE: I don't know if this is the same problem the OP is dealing with.  I can move this post if you think it belongs elsewhere.
